metadata.name: Toccata #36
metadata.description:
Toccata is a piece about decay, about the impermanent. The emergence over time or, rather, progression of entropy is a key characteristic of our universe. Everything evolves to nothing. We as mortal beings have sometimes trouble reconciling with this idea. Humans have sought immortality for millennia, be it through ancient potions or modern medicine, be it from leaving a legacy that we feel will stand the test of time. It will, only to decay later than us.

Toccata is a piece about change. Change lies at the heart of human cognition and human nature. Our thoughts and our emotions happen over time, and are a function of the change that is both around us and at the very core of our selves. Change comes in nature in cycles. Seasons of growth, seasons of ripe fruits of life, seasons of decay, of death, rebirth.

Toccata is music. We find music to convey some of the deepest streams of human condition, connecting it to some other form of being. Music also happens over time, and music happens because of change. Music encodes our feelings better than any other aid we may have. Toccata incorporates this at its very core, as the main sound is Andreas' family piano where he learned to play, sampled this past July.

Read more about the piece, and the collaboration between Marcelo and Andreas on andreasrau.eu/toccata

---

Basic controls:
- Click on the piece or press spacebar to start it (WebAudio requires user intervention for the music to start). Once the music has started, again click or press spacebar to play/pause.
- Press “s” to save a still at the current resolution
- Press “r” to start recording a video at the current resolution, then “r” again to stop.

---

WebM audio-video recording performed using the library RecordRTC by https://muazkhan.com/, MIT licence.

metadata.name: barcode(fxhash) #86
metadata.description:
[UPDATED: There was a bug in the first edition of this token that has been solved in this. All minters of the previous edition, has a reserve of 2]

barcode(fxhash) converts the ascii characters from the transaction hash of the token (fxhash variable) into barcodes for each of 51 characters. It uses Code 39 (https://github.com/graphicore/librebarcode), so it is not case sensitive. Each iteration has from 1 to 8 columns, and from 1 to 8 rows, and the frist N characters of the fxhash are displayed in one of first N positions (first 2 characters are discarted). If the number of characters is greater than 49 (length of fxhash discarting 'oo'), the boxes will continue to be filled, returning from the third character of fxhash.

Features generated by fxrand() random function:

-num_chars: number of characters displayed. from 1 to 64. They are the first N characters of fxhash.
-has_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash'.
-show_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash' and these are all displayed.
-columns: number of columns (1-8).
-rows: number of rows (1-8).
-color_mode: color mode white (light) or black (dark).
-separacio: factor of separation between barcodes (1.1, 1.5 or 2)
-scale_type: scale type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-rotate_type: rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-transparent: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes has a transparent background.
-squares: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes width=height.
-main_shadow: blur value for main shadow.
-exterior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-interior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)


(There are more values generated by fxrand() not shown as Feature)

click to show all fxhash barcodes, wich are displayed.

metadata.name: 🟧🟦 QT 🟦🟧 #86
metadata.description:
🟧🟦 Qt is a unique interactive PFP.

🔶As you move the mouse, QT eyes monitor your movements and react accordingly. If you're lucky enough to have laser eyes, you have a QT protecting you. There are several gift hearts and diamonds around you that you can pick up(There is no doubt that you will use them somewhere.). Your QTs bring nouns and behavioral adjectives with them. In the gift that's going around the platform, you'll find it.

A total of thirty rare groups are considered for QTs, making them unique among PFPs and allowing you to have diverse and exclusive QTs.

🔷QT is not just an NFT. To make significant events more enjoyable, QT is with you. All you need to do is own QTs and follow them. You will be surprised by QTs. 1011 girls and 1011 boys will mint in the first series of QTs in 2022. At the opening of the 2022 World Cup, the first QT Boy pieces were minted.

🤝Saleh.C4d and  ArashMP collaborated on QT.

✅ you can save the image in the following sizes:

⌨️ Key number 1️⃣ 1080 pixels

metadata.name: Encapsulated #112
metadata.description:
Have you ever felt fear? Have you ever felt tired? Have you ever felt trapped and watched? The bars of the big cities are supposed to bring us protection, but in the end, we are encapsulated in this big prison.

This project was made thinking about that feeling of prison ourselves and will participate in the #fxhashturnsone event. 

Fully made with p5.js and p5.grain

metadata.name: Crosswalk Monsoon #13
metadata.description:
The story behind this collection is that there isn't really a story behind this collection. It is the result of play, tinkering, and curiosity.

One of the beautiful things about generative art is how we can achieve drastically different results simply by modifying a few parameters or lines of code. As my first release here on fxhash was 'Sabler', it felt fitting that my release for #fxhashturnsone would itself be a modified version of that 'Sabler' algorithm, albeit giving drastically different results.

It is notable for the fact that this is perhaps my most 'chaotic' collection yet, letting go of carefully considered proportions, angles and positioning and here leaving that in the hands of the computer. In a way, this simple act represents several design decisions I never would have imagined myself making a year ago, highlighting my growth as a generative artist over the past year.

It is also a reflection of the inspiration gained from many of the artists and boundary-pushers in the space that each time unlock and encourage creations beyond the immediate comfort zone. For that, this is a 'Thank You' to all of you.

With that, here's to many more years of generative beauty and inspiration on fxhash and beyond.

As with previous collections, I highly recommend viewing the images at full size and savouring the details and the chaos up close. Pressing 'S' will save a 6000 x 6000 px PNG file.

50% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

metadata.name: Annum #8112
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

50% of primary sales go to Savepakistan.

metadata.name: Nebula, Solitude #49
metadata.description:
Nebula is one of the most magnificent stellar phenomena to behold. It is a distinct luminescent part of the interstellar medium, which consists of ionized gas and cosmic dust. Nebulae are often star-forming regions, where stars are born in solitude but surrounded by beautiful light and matter.

In this series, I continue the exploration of color and gravity, the effect of mass on speed, the effect of speed on hue, and how light can change by passing through big particles and dust systems.

I also want to let you participate in the creation of your artwork variation too. Each iteration is a unique and unpredictable dance of light in the dust and gravitation between matter clusters, however,  with the controls listed below, you can change the probability of light/dust blocks as well as the tiling layout.

[L] - create a new layout
[S] - reshuffle the current layout

[Shift] + [1] - change dust blocks probability to 0.0 and reshuffle the current layout
[Shift] + [2] - —//— 0.2
[Shift] + [3] - —//— 0.4
[Shift] + [4] - —//— 0.6
[Shift] + [5] - —//— 0.8
[Shift] + [6] - —//— 1.0

Basics:
[A] - skip/restart the animation

[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Experimental zone:
[E] - toggle endless animation
[0] - save the current frame in low resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.

Use Chrome 107 for the best experience, other browsers are significantly slower on this artwork, visual results also may vary.

Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0
